Part A – BLE device: send packets
On a microcontroller or other BLE device, you expose a GATT characteristic that you notify with data. That depends on your device stack (e.g., Nordic SDK / ESP32), so I’ll just name it:

Service UUID: SERVICE_UUID
Characteristic UUID: CHAR_UUID
You program that device so that whenever it has data (a “packet”), it pushes it as bytes on that characteristic.

Part B – Windows PC: receive via BLE and send to HTTP API
Install dependencies (in PowerShell or Git Bash):

bash

pip install bleak requests

Python script (run on your Windows PC):

python

import asyncio
import json
import requests
from bleak import BleakClient

BLE_ADDRESS = "AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF"      # MAC or ID of your BLE device
SERVICE_UUID = "0000xxxx-0000-1000-8000-00805f9b34fb"
CHAR_UUID = "0000yyyy-0000-1000-8000-00805f9b34fb"

API_URL = "https://example.com/ingest"  # Your backend HTTP API

def send_to_api(payload: bytes):
    # Convert bytes to something your API accepts (here: hex string)
    data = {
        "source": "ble_device_1",
        "payload_hex": payload.hex(),
    }
    try:
        r = requests.post(API_URL, json=data, timeout=5)
        r.raise_for_status()
    except Exception as e:
        print("HTTP send failed:", e)

def notification_handler(_: int, data: bytearray):
    # Called every time the BLE device sends a notification on CHAR_UUID
    print("Got BLE packet:", data.hex())
    send_to_api(bytes(data))

async def main():
    async with BleakClient(BLE_ADDRESS) as client:
        print("Connected to BLE device:", BLE_ADDRESS)

        await client.start_notify(CHAR_UUID, notification_handler)
        print("Listening for BLE packets; Ctrl+C to exit.")
        while True:
            await asyncio.sleep(1)

What this does:

Connects to your BLE device (BLE_ADDRESS).
Subscribes to notifications on CHAR_UUID.
Every time the device pushes data over Bluetooth RF, notification_handler runs and:
Logs the packet.
Sends it via HTTPS JSON (requests.post) to API_URL.
So:

Bluetooth RF carries the short‑range link (device → PC).
IP/TLS/HTTP/JSON carry the backend part (PC → server).
Nothing in <current_tab_state> is transmitted; it’s just local Wave UI state on your PC unless you explicitly send it.

if __name__ == "__main__":
    asyncio.run(main())
